The Delta State governor, Ifeanyi Okowa, his wife and daughter, have all recovered from COVID-19 infection. The Interview had reported that Okowa, his wife and daughter tested positive for COVID-19 and gone into isolation two weeks ago. Okowa, however, announced that he, his wife and daughter have recovered from COVID-19 on Tuesday via his twitter handle. READ ALSO: Okowa, Wife And Daughter Test Positive For COVID-19 He said “My wife, my daughter and I have tested negative for COVID 19, along with other members of the family. We give God all praise and wish to appreciate all who have interceded for us in prayers.” Appealing to the public to adhere to safety guidelines, Okowa said it was the collective responsibility of everyone to help stop the spread of the virus. READ ALSO: Nigeria’s COVID-19 Cases Hit 254 As Delta State Records First Patient “I appeal to all residing in Delta to obey all instructions/ regulations in our collective fight to stop the transmission of the virus. God bless you all”, he said. With this development, Okowa becomes the sixth governor to have contracted and recovered from COVID-19. Others governors who have tested positive for COVID-19 include; Bala Mohammed, Governor of Bauchi State; Nasir El-Rufai, the governor of Kaduna State, Seyi Makinde, Governor of Oyo State, Okezie Ikpeazu, Governor of Abia State and Rotimi Akeredolu of Ondo State. According to Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) Delta State has recorded 1,359 cases, discharged 583 patients and recorded 31 deaths so far. The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) on Monday reported 595 new cases of COVID-19 in the country taking the total number of confirmed cases 33,153. The number of patients discharged now stands at 13,671 and the death toll is 744. At least 20 states reported new cases and nine states now have more than 1,000 confirmed cases. READ ALSO: Nigeria’s COVID-19 Deaths Now 740 Only seven states; Kofi, Cross River, Taraba, Yobe, Ekiti, Zamfara and Kebbi have less than 100 cases each.
Lagos State  which reported 156 new cases now has a total of 12,583 confirmed cases. The Federal Capital Territory (FCT) has 2,675 while Kaduna is the latest state to confirm more than 1,000 cases. READ ALSO: COVID-19 Can Spread Through Air – Chikwe Ihekweazu The NCDC update showed Oyo reported 141 new cases and the FCT recorded 99, Edo had 47 and Kaduna had 27. Ondo reported 22, Rivers had 20, Osun had 17, Imo had 13, Plateau reported 10, while Nasarawa and Anambra reported eight each. READ ALSO: Nigeria’s COVID-19 Cases Near 32,000 Kano, Benue and Borno states recorded five each, Ogun reported four, Taraba and Gombe had three each, and Kebbi and Cross Rivers each had one case.